			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=47980&amp;sid=8cf1235613d6d69890daf1635e23f414#p47980"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38867&amp;sid=8cf1235613d6d69890daf1635e23f414">jovial01</a></strong> on Sat Oct 23, 2010 11:40 pm			<br />([msg=47980]see Re: Secure file deletion[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">What do you all think is better:<br />Deleting a file then trying to overwrite the memory repeatedly to obscure the evidence of it being there in the first place?<br />OR<br />Digitally shredding the file making it mathematically/computationally infeasible to put back together again? <br /><br />A combination of the two seems better, but if I had to choose, I would choose the last option. Any thoughts?<br /><br />Also, what do you all think is the best method for shredding files, do you trust 3rd party software? How about writing your own algorithms? Ideas?</div>

			
		</div>

